Governors in Western counties are front runners in the August elections, a study indicates.The study was carried out by the University of Nairobi&rsquo;s department of Political Science and Public Administration. It sampled 200 respondents in Western between July 19 and October 5 last year.The respondents were asked who they thought was most suitable to be governor in each of the counties.The survey rates Kakamega Governor Wycliffe Oparanya as the top performer at 71 per cent. Vihiga&rsquo;s Moses Akaranga is second at 60 per cent, followed by Trans Nzoia&rsquo;s Patrick Khaemba at 58 per cent. Bungoma&rsquo;s Kenneth Lusaka is fourth with 53 per cent and Busia Governor Sospeter Ojaamong last with 45 per cent.In Kakamega, the survey rates Senator Boni Khalwale at 17 per cent, Lugari MP Ayub Savula at seven per cent and aspirant Marble Muruli at five per cent.In Vihiga, Senator George Khaniri is rated at 15 per cent, Emuhaya MP Wilber Otichilo at seven per cent and Jairus Amayi at five per cent. In Trans Nzoia, Geoffrey Shihundu is rated at 11 per cent, Joshua Kutuny at seven per cent and former Kwanza MP Noah Wekesa at two per cent.In Bungoma, the survey rates former electoral commissioner Jack Tumwa at 17 per cent, former Kanduyi MP Alfred Khang&rsquo;ati at 13 per cent, Stephen Mutoro at eight per cent and Wycliffe Wangamati at four per cent.In Busia, Funyula MP Paul Otuoma is rated at 35 per cent, Humphrey Nakitare at nine per cent and Vincent Sidai at five per cent.